President Barack Obama announced his intent to nominate Joseph A. Smith, Jr. as the Director of the Federal Housing Finance Agency. Smith is currently the North Carolina Commissioner of Banks, a position he has held since June 2002. As Commissioner, he is responsible for supervising banks and thrift institutions, regulating mortgage banking and brokerage firms, and overseeing consumer finance enterprises. Smith is also the Immediate Past Chair of the Conference of State Bank Supervisors and a founding member of the Board of Managers of State Regulatory Registry LLC. He holds degrees from Davidson College and the University of Virginia Law School and is licensed to practice law in New York and North Carolina. President Obama praised Smith's expertise and commitment to strengthening the housing finance system for the American people.